Irked by the persistently high rate of child malnutrition in Northern Nigeria, state’s assemblies in the region have called for the adoption of homegrown solution for curative and preventive measures against the problem. The assemblies have also expressed concern over the dreaded impacts of the problem on the economy and productivity of the region as over 2.5 a million children were said to have been suffering from malnutrition in the area. This was contained in a communique issued at the end of separate retreat for Kano and Katsina states assemblies, and relevant committees on prevention of acute child malnutrition organized by Civil Society Legislative Advocacy Centre (CISLAC) held at Dutse, Jigawa state capital, recently. According to the communiqué issued at the end of the event, using locally available resources including the production of Ready to Use Therapeutic Food (RUTF) must be considered to address the root cause of the problems. Stakeholders noted that continued dependence  on foreign aid, such as UNICEF intervention can’t provide a sustainable solution to the problems which is purely domestic, therefore the affected states must look inward and come up with a policy that can give sustainable solution to the menace. The statement added that the focus must also be made in promoting Infant and Young Child Feeding ( IYCF) programme and exclusive breastfeeding practice as critical measures to prevent problems. The assemblies then called for coordinated multi-sectoral approaches and synergy in financing nutrition programme, mobilising human resources, effective engagement of community groups to holistically make the child malnutrition problems as history of the first in the region.